Architecture plan for Issue #151: Remove welcome-email sending from the subscription flow

Current structure:
- backend/: Rust Axum API server with route modules under backend/src/routes, application wiring in backend/src/app.rs, configuration in backend/src/config.rs, SQLx/PostgreSQL persistence in backend/src/db.rs, and currently email plumbing in backend/src/email.rs.
- frontend/: Vite/React SPA. Subscription UI posts to POST /api/subscriptions and expects the existing success/duplicate/error response shape.
- shared/: TypeScript constants and DTO contracts, including subscription request/response types.

Issue dependency plan:
- There is only one implementation issue, so no cross-issue dependency ordering is required.
- Backend subscription persistence and response behavior must remain unchanged: new subscriptions return 201 with already_subscribed=false; duplicates return 200 with already_subscribed=true.
- Frontend and shared DTOs should not need changes unless backend response contracts change, which this issue explicitly says not to do.

Design decisions:
- Remove email side effects from the subscription route by deleting the send_welcome_email import/call in backend/src/routes/subscriptions.rs.
- Remove email_client from AppDependencies and constructor wiring in backend/src/app.rs because no route will need it.
- Remove the email module export and backend/src/email.rs once unused.
- Remove email-related runtime config fields from backend/src/config.rs if they are only used by the deleted email client; keep unrelated app config intact.
- Drop reqwest from backend/Cargo.toml if no other backend module uses it.
- Update docs/environment notes to stop advertising welcome-email delivery if they become stale.
- Validate with cargo test, npm typecheck/build where feasible.
